<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-516-064  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 516 064.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 4 1990 v24 n23 pSR13(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Alsop's advice to PC vendors: worry, users unhappy. (PC Letterpublisher Stewart Alsop) (interview)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zottola, Lory.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>PC Letter publisher Stewart Alsop states that microcomputervendors are not delivering the products users are interested inbecause they are caught between technical changes and customerswho do not understand technology but are looking for usefulapplications.andP;  The OSF/1 operating system was chosen because IBMforced it in, and users of proprietary technology are oftenhappier than those attempting to implement 'open' systems.andO;Start-up companies have difficulty becoming industry leadersbecause they lack power, and firms with power do not always havethe motivation to hold onto leadership.andP;  Apple has built a $4.5billion business on its Macintosh computer, but Microsoft andothers will catch up with the Mac technology by 1995.andP;  Apple mustdo innovative work in multimedia and digital audio and video toretain its leadership role.andP;  The Mac industry is awaiting theSystem 7.0 operating system before engaging in new development.andO;Most DOS users are happy with their system despite itslimitations; efforts to find truly new DOS applications havefailed.andP;  Future innovations will include new software for the NeXTcomputer and multimedia applications.andP;  OS/2 is a fundamentallywrong design for a microcomputer operating system, but Unix facesits own problems with standardization and competition.andP;  BothNovell Inc and Microsoft are working on the wrong networkoperating system model.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersComputer industryVendor RelationsCustomer RelationsUser NeedsForecastingFuture of ComputingInterview.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andO;Person:    Alsop, Stewart (interviews).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>